<paragraph id="8BC3C5308E53FFBEFF1AFC07DB11FBF4" blockId="8.[163,620,1020,1042]" box="[163,620,1020,1042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<heading id="D08B725C8E53FFBEFF1AFC07DB11FBF4" box="[163,620,1020,1042]" fontSize="8" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" reason="2">
<emphasis id="B90819228E53FFBEFF1AFC07DB11FBF4" bold="true" box="[163,620,1020,1042]" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
Key to the Arabian species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7CBEB38E53FFBEFE5CFC07DB11FBF4" authorityName="EICHELBAUM" authorityYear="1908" box="[485,620,1020,1042]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pinophilinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90819228E53FFBEFE5CFC07DB11FBF4" bold="true" box="[485,620,1020,1042]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Pinophilinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36696BB8E53FFBFFF1AFBD9DD52FEC4" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" type="key">
<key id="FFED92018E53FFBFFF1AFBD9DD52FEC4" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<keyStep id="3088DD958E53FFBEFF1AFBD9DD53FB07" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<paragraph id="8BC3C5308E53FFBEFF1AFBD9DD53FB75" blockId="8.[163,1070,1058,1590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<keyLead id="308D66058E53FFBEFF1AFBD9DD53FB75" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
1 Large species; body length approximately 
<quantity id="4C8468D58E53FFBEFDC4FBD9DBB3FBD1" box="[637,718,1058,1079]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" unit="mm" value="7.5">7.5 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody&gt; 3.0 mm. Antenna approximately 
<quantity id="4C8468D58E53FFBEFE03FBC2DB7AFBA8" box="[442,519,1081,1102]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
long and slender; antennomere III approximately 3 times as long as broad; IX distinctly oblong. Coloration of body pale-reddish. Body, particularly abdomen, with coarse and dense punctation. 
<collectingRegion id="49B80BD28E53FFBEFD57FB9CDAF9FB9A" box="[750,900,1127,1148]" country="Egypt" name="Shamal Sina'" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Sinai Peninsula</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E53FFBEFC29FB9CDAB1FB9A" box="[912,972,1127,1148]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="7.[163,208,1544,1564]" captionTargetBox="[162,1070,861,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-281@7.[164,1068,1140,1529]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Map 1: Distribution of Arabian Pinophilinus species: P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (triangle); P. spinosus nov.sp. (circles); P. socotranus ASSING (diamond)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341018" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341018/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Map 1</figureCitation>
).............. ......................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7CBEB38E53FFBEFCE9FB84DD53FB75" authority="(KOCH)" baseAuthorityName="Koch" baseAuthorityYear="1934" box="[848,1070,1150,1172]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pinophilinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schatzmayri">
<emphasis id="B90819228E53FFBEFCE9FB84DAA2FB75" box="[848,991,1150,1172]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">P. schatzmayri</emphasis>
(KOCH)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3C5308E53FFBEFF1AFB65DD53FB07" blockId="8.[163,1070,1058,1590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<keyLead id="308D66058E53FFBEFF1AFB65DD53FB07" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
- Distinctly smaller and more slender species; body length &lt;7.0 mm; length of forebody &lt;
<quantity id="4C8468D58E53FFBEFF67FB4ED856FB2C" box="[222,299,1205,1226]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
. Antenna &lt;
<quantity id="4C8468D58E53FFBEFE1AFB4ED893FB2C" box="[419,494,1205,1226]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long and less slender; antennomere III at most twice as long as broad; IX at least as broad as long..........................................................................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="3088DD958E53FFBEFF1AFB10DD6EF9D0" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<paragraph id="8BC3C5308E53FFBEFF1AFB10DD53FA5E" blockId="8.[163,1070,1058,1590]" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<keyLead id="308D66058E53FFBEFF1AFB10DD53FA5E" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
2 Body dark-brown. Eyes small, shorter than postocular region in dorsal view (ASSING 2012: figure 11). Antenna shorter (
<quantity id="4C8468D58E53FFBEFDA7FAF9DB16FAF1" box="[542,619,1282,1303]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
) and less slender (ASSING 2012: figure 10); antennomere III approximately 1.5 times as long as broad; IV-V indistinctly oblong. Pronotum somewhat flattened and distinctly narrowed posteriorly (ASSING 2012: figure 11). Head and pronotum with moderately dense punctation; interstices on average broader than diameter of punctures. ♂: sternite VIII with very small posterior excision (ASSING 2012: figure 13); aedeagus symmetric and apically very acute in ventral view; internal sac without large sclerotized spine (ASSING 2012: figures 14-15). 
<collectingCountry id="F36B85A08E53FFBEFC73FA75D879FA5C" name="Socotra Island" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Socotra Island</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="F36B85A08E53FFBEFEA9FA5ED82AFA5C" box="[272,343,1445,1466]" name="Yemen" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Yemen</collectingCountry>
) (
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E53FFBEFED5FA5ED8D7FA5C" box="[364,426,1445,1466]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="7.[163,208,1544,1564]" captionTargetBox="[162,1070,861,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-281@7.[164,1068,1140,1529]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Map 1: Distribution of Arabian Pinophilinus species: P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (triangle); P. spinosus nov.sp. (circles); P. socotranus ASSING (diamond)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341018" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341018/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Map 1</figureCitation>
)..................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7CBEB38E53FFBEFCE4FA5EDD53FA5E" authority="ASSING" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2012" box="[861,1070,1445,1466]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pinophilinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="socotranus">
<emphasis id="B90819228E53FFBEFCE4FA5EDA9DFA5C" box="[861,992,1445,1466]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">P. socotranus</emphasis>
ASSING
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC3C5308E53FFBFFF1AFA3FDD52FEC4" blockId="8.[163,1070,1058,1590]" lastBlockId="9.[201,1071,199,290]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="150" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
<keyLead id="308D66058E53FFBEFF1AFA3FDD6EF9D0" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">
- Body pale-reddish. Eyes rather large, distinctly longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antennae longer (
<quantity id="4C8468D58E53FFBEFE76FA20DB58FA16" box="[463,549,1499,1520]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="149" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
) and more slender (
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E53FFBEFCB4FA20DA32FA16" box="[781,847,1499,1520]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1403,1423]" captionTargetBox="[176,1060,209,1383]" captionTargetId="figure-0@6.[171,1060,209,1395]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1-8: Pinophilinus spinosus nov.sp. (1-5) and P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (6-8): (1, 6) habitus; (2, 7) forebody; (3, 8) abdomen; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3, 6-8: 1.0 mm; 4-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341016" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341016/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); antennomere III approximately twice as long as broad; IV-V approximately 1.5 times as long as broad. Pronotum more convex in cross-section and less strongly narrowed posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E53FFBEFC75F9F1DD7AF9F9" box="[972,1031,1546,1567]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1403,1423]" captionTargetBox="[176,1060,209,1383]" captionTargetId="figure-0@6.[171,1060,209,1395]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1-8: Pinophilinus spinosus nov.sp. (1-5) and P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (6-8): (1, 6) habitus; (2, 7) forebody; (3, 8) abdomen; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3, 6-8: 1.0 mm; 4-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341016" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341016/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="149">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Head and pronotum with dense punctation; interstices on average narrower than
</keyLead>
<keyLead id="308D66058E52FFBFFF70FF3CDD52FEC4" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">
<keyStep id="3088DD958E52FFBFFF70FF3CDD52FEC4" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">
diameter of punctures (
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E52FFBFFE02FF3CD881FF3A" box="[443,508,199,220]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1403,1423]" captionTargetBox="[176,1060,209,1383]" captionTargetId="figure-0@6.[171,1060,209,1395]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1-8: Pinophilinus spinosus nov.sp. (1-5) and P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (6-8): (1, 6) habitus; (2, 7) forebody; (3, 8) abdomen; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3, 6-8: 1.0 mm; 4-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341016" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341016/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). ♂: sternite VIII with larger and deeper posterior excision (
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E52FFBFFE92FF25D811FF15" box="[299,364,222,243]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1403,1423]" captionTargetBox="[176,1060,209,1383]" captionTargetId="figure-0@6.[171,1060,209,1395]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1-8: Pinophilinus spinosus nov.sp. (1-5) and P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (6-8): (1, 6) habitus; (2, 7) forebody; (3, 8) abdomen; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3, 6-8: 1.0 mm; 4-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341016" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341016/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); aedeagus with slightly asymmetric and much less acute apex in ventral view; internal sac with large sclerotized spine (
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E52FFBFFD43FF0DDA44FEED" box="[762,825,246,267]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1403,1423]" captionTargetBox="[176,1060,209,1383]" captionTargetId="figure-0@6.[171,1060,209,1395]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1-8: Pinophilinus spinosus nov.sp. (1-5) and P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (6-8): (1, 6) habitus; (2, 7) forebody; (3, 8) abdomen; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3, 6-8: 1.0 mm; 4-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341016" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341016/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Southwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F36B85A08E52FFBFFC64FF0DD877FEC4" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="1347D9B58E52FFBFFEAEFEF6D82FFEC4" box="[279,338,269,290]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="7.[163,208,1544,1564]" captionTargetBox="[162,1070,861,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-281@7.[164,1068,1140,1529]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Map 1: Distribution of Arabian Pinophilinus species: P. schatzmayri (KOCH) (triangle); P. spinosus nov.sp. (circles); P. socotranus ASSING (diamond)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5341018" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5341018/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">Map 1</figureCitation>
)....................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C7CBEB38E52FFBFFCCCFEF6DA9EFEC4" authority="Assing &amp; Schülke &amp; M.R &amp; A.S, 2013" authorityName="Assing &amp; Schülke &amp; M.R &amp; A.S" authorityYear="2013" box="[885,995,269,290]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pinophilinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="150" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="B90819228E52FFBFFCCCFEF6DA9EFEC4" box="[885,995,269,290]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="150">P. spinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23BA4598E52FFBFFC50FEF6DD52FEC4" box="[1001,1071,269,290]" pageId="9" pageNumber="150" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
